===Etymology 1===
From Middle English ''[[moder]]'' ("mother") < Old English ''[[modor|mōdor]]''. Cognates include Modern {{Gr.}} [[μητέρα]], German ''[[Mutter]]'', Russian [[мать]] (mat’) and Latin ''[[mater]]'', [[Mycenaean]] Greek
'''''ma-te-re''''' '''[[ματήρ]]''' (''mater'') and Sanskrit Matru.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A woman who has at least one child.
#: ''My sister-in-law has just become a mother.''
# One’s female [[parent]].
#: ''I am visiting my mother today.''
# {{figuratively}} Female [[ancestor]].
# {{figuratively}} Source or origin, viewed affectionately.
#: ''The Mediterranean was mother to many cultures and languages.''
# A stupid person

